    description:
      "A Song dynasty medical formulary combining prescriptions by the polymath Shen Kuo (沈括, 1031–1095) with pharmaceutical essays and clinical notes by Su Shi (蘇軾, 1037–1101). Despite the joint attribution, the work was not a true collaboration: Shen Kuo compiled his collection of tested remedies independently, and later editors interleaved Su Shi's writings on herbs, drugs, and medical theory. The result is an unusually literary medical text. Shen Kuo's contributions are practical and clinical — verified prescriptions for wind disorders, abdominal ailments, women's diseases, and paediatric conditions, with precise dosages and preparation methods. Su Shi's contributions are discursive and personal — essays on pulse diagnosis, the five difficulties of medical practice, botanical observations made during his southern exiles, and reflections on pharmacological theory drawn from his wide reading. The ten volumes cover herbal materia medica, moxibustion techniques, internal and external medicine, ophthalmology, dermatology, and folk remedies. The work preserves valuable clinical knowledge from the Northern Song period and offers a rare window into how two of China's greatest intellectuals engaged with the medical tradition.",
