    description:
      "A major work of Polish Romantic philosophy by Karol Libelt, published in two volumes (1845 and 1874). The first part, 'Samowładztwo rozumu i objawy filozofii słowiańskiej' (The Sovereignty of Reason and Manifestations of Slavic Philosophy), critiques German idealism — Kant, Fichte, Hegel, Schelling — arguing that pure reason alone cannot grasp reality and that Slavic thought, grounded in imagination and national feeling, offers a corrective. The second part, 'System Umnictwa' (The System of Imaginative Knowledge), presents Libelt's positive philosophical programme: a theory of imagination ('umnictwo') as the highest human faculty, alongside a philosophy of nature and aesthetics. The work is a foundational document of 19th-century Polish intellectual life, arguing for a distinctly Slavic contribution to European philosophy at a time of national subjugation.",
