      "The foundational work of the 'romaneto', a distinctively Czech genre that Arbes pioneered — a novella blending detective fiction, philosophical speculation, and the supernatural. The narrator encounters a mysterious stranger obsessed with František Balko's 1667 altarpiece depicting the death of Saint Francis Xavier in Prague's St. Nicholas Church. Through meticulous observation and mathematical analysis, the stranger believes he has discovered that the painting encodes a cryptographic map to treasure hidden by the Jesuits before their 1773 suppression. The text explores the boundary between rational inquiry and obsessive delusion, set against the atmospheric backdrop of Baroque Prague. Arbes's influence on later Czech literature, particularly Čapek's approach to mystery and speculation, is considerable.",
    sourceUrl: "https://cs.wikisource.org/wiki/Svatý_Xaverius",
