      "A historical novel set during the English siege of Quebec in 1690, when Sir William Phips led a fleet of thirty-four ships against the capital of New France. The story follows the young François de Bienville, a soldier in the garrison, as he contends with Iroquois raiders, English invaders, and personal loss during the desperate defence of the colony. The novel portrays the courage of the small French-Canadian population, the brutal tactics of frontier warfare, and the decisive leadership of Governor Frontenac, whose defiant refusal to surrender became a defining moment in Canadian history. First published in 1870, the novel is the second in Marmette's cycle of four historical romances covering the colonial period.",
