    description:
      "A collection of 175 sonnets published in 1904 by Pamphile Le May, one of French Canada's most celebrated poets. The collection is organised into 19 thematic sections exploring biblical narratives (Eve, Adam, the Deluge, Moses), Gospel scenes (the Visitation, Magdalene, the Crucifixion), religious meditations (sanctuary lamps, bells, angels), tributes to Canadian figures (Laurier, Mercier, Fréchette), Canadian history (Cartier, Champlain, Wolfe and Montcalm, the Patriots of 1837), rural life (ploughing, sowing, harvest, the forest), love, the celestial spheres, landscapes of Quebec (Lake Beauport, Montmorency Falls), and philosophical reflections on time, memory, and mortality. The title Gouttelettes (droplets) suggests each sonnet as a distilled essence of thought and feeling, capturing moments of spiritual insight, patriotic sentiment, domestic affection, and contemplation of nature. Le May's sonnets reflect the values of 19th-century French-Canadian society—Catholic piety, attachment to the land, reverence for family and nation—while demonstrating his mastery of the traditional French sonnet form.",
